segments.text: Can you tell me about your early life, where and when you were born, your family, that sort of thing?
I was born April 28, 1916, in Sutton County, Texas.
Sonora is a county seat.
My parents lived on a ranch.
And so my early years were spent there.
What was your ranch's name?
What?
What was the ranch's name?
The ranch?
Well, my father was W.W. Williamson, and we didn't have a name for the ranch.
But he ranched there for about 35 years.
Do you have any brothers and sisters?
Yes.
I have one sister and three brothers.
Can you tell me about your education and the jobs you've held?
Actually, I started the school in Sonora.
And at that time, I guess the age to start was six years old.
But we were the closest house to the school.
My mother became a great friend of the first grade teacher.
And I was the only one at home.
So the teacher would tell my mother what she was doing with the class at school and let her have the books and all.
So my mother had been a teacher, so she taught me.
So that's how I got such an early start at age five.
And when I was six at the end of April, she told my mother to let me come on to school that I was six then.
So I really was in school.
less than a year, but she promoted me.
And so, my mother talked with the superintendent to see if I should start back through the first grade, but he said it wasn't important that I could handle the work, so I just went on from there.
So that made me graduate early, and graduate early from college.
I've been 16 less than a month, and I graduated from high school.
20 less a month when I graduated from college.
And I've been about it during high school.
I don't know.
We moved from the ranch in Sutton County in, I guess, 1928.

and uh my mother yeah my mother had um maintained two homes while we were in school in sonora i finished the seventh grade there and uh she decided that she was just not gonna do that anymore she never learned to drive so she couldn't drive in this school so uh
who moves the ranch in our county.
I was in eighth grade when I was 12.
And there's a big question about how was I going to get to school, because there weren't any school buses yet.
So I said, well, I'd love to ride a horse, so I'll just ride.
My dad said, well, I want you to understand, if you say you're going to ride, you're going to ride rain or shine.
And he meant it.
And they got me this rain slipper that buckled around each leg.
And I rode seven miles to school.
seven miles back, 14 mile run trip.
Quite an experience.
Kind of lost my love of horseback riding.
How long did it take?
As I remember, it was about 30 minutes.
But my mother was always afraid I was going to kill the horse because I ran it all the way both ways.
And it was quite an experience if it was cold and icy.
Winters were colder back then.
And
Anyway, I survived.
Don't think I was even sick that year.
Did he ever, like, throw you or give you trouble?
The first day I rode to school, he'd never been around that many people.
I don't know, it's not read straight up, but I stayed on.
And his worst habit was, I guess his worst, when there was a thunderstorm.
Of course, I had to hitch him to a tree, and he whined around the tree.
pull his head back and break the bridle and take off.
So I used to have to hunt him all the time after a storm.
And he had a bad habit of, he got excited, he'd run away with me.
But anyway, as I say, I survived it and that was the only year that I had the right.
Next year, my sister taught that school because she graduated from college and
The fellow she was to marry had one more year in Texas.
And so she taught that school and of course she drove us.
You don't know about the next year when I was 14.
My parents bought me a little green Ford Sport Roadster with a rumble seat.
And I drove 23 miles into school in Menard.
over dirt roads, which meant if it rained I'd get stuck sometimes.
And they tell me that I drove a little speedy because I wanted to get there to play tennis before school started.
And I played late in the afternoon after school was out.
My mother always insisted I get home by dark.
So that was my junior year.
What else do we need to know?
Do you have any curfews?
Any what?
Curfews.
Besides, you know, being home by dark.
Oh.
Well.
It kind of drove my mother crazy because there was always some event I needed to be there for in the evenings.
And so she finally decided that my senior year she would let us have an apartment in this little town.
So I wouldn't be on the road at all times if not.
Then you went on to the University of Texas?
Yeah.
You know, this is just a small school.
I think there were 36 in my class.
And you were valedictorian?
I was valedictorian.
My mother had been a teacher, and it just sort of ran in the family of my oldest sister.
My oldest sister, actually.
She was valedictorian.
And then my next brother was salutatorian.
My mother was very disappointed in him.
The next brother was valedictorian.
He graduated the day he was 16.
And unfortunately, he died one week before he was to go to college.
He was around four years older than I.
That's something that nobody would die of now, because he'd been hurt going to help a neighbor fight a fire.
And then you went on to college when you were 16?
Yeah, but see, we didn't have any counselors or anything.
This is a very small school.
Anyway, I guess I should have, my husband would have said I should have majored in home ed because I didn't have a lot of those skills.
But instead of that, I picked something less practical.
Anyway, so I go to the University of Texas.
Freshman, 16 years old.
Stayed in Little Field on.
And the interesting thing about that that I learned many, many years later
George Littlefield was one of the biggest benefactors of the University of Texas.
Of course, I didn't just live in Littlefield Dorm.
It didn't mean much to me.
Walked past Littlefield Home on the way to campus.
The statues that are on the campus there were put there with Littlefield money.
The big fountain with the bronze horses.
It's Littlefield Fountain.
Found out many years later that at one time, he owned a ranch that I grew up on.
uh, in an abstract which I didn't realize that had a copy of George Littlefield's will in one of the abstracts of the rank.
But anyway, uh,
What do you know about school women?
So you went to UT in 1938?
No, I went there in 1932.
Were there a lot of women there during that time?
Oh, there wasn't any total enrollment.
As I remember it, it was about 6,500 when I went there.
And when I graduated, I think there were about
2,000 more.
So, like A&M, you know, it had just grown beyond everybody's expectations.
And I think it's quite different than what it is now.
If we had a date or anything, we had to sign out and had to sign in.
We had strict hours and
Anyway, at the end of that freshman year, I was elected back on the upper class council.
They were elected back about 12 girls, two, sort of like the RAs now, I suppose, the bachelors, the freshmen.
And I stayed there that year.
I was president of Dawn.
I don't know why, but somebody stuck me with that.
And then I was elected back again, so I stayed in the freshman girls' dorm for three years.
And then my last year, my senior year, I stayed in Charlotte.
And you graduated in 1936?
I graduated in 36.
You were a 20?
I've been 20 less than a month.
So, you know, it was not to my advantage to graduate that young because it was kind of hard to get a job teaching, which I did one whole year.
Um, you said, we're going to get to teaching in a minute.
I had various activities, I don't know what all, but I served on student government two years.
It was called Student Assembly over there.
From the College of Education, or School of Education, whichever it was.
You said your husband said you should have taken homemaking.
Why do you say that?
Oh, yes, yes.
Why do you say that?
Because I couldn't cook.
And he was from a family of boys, and his mother had been a real good cook.
And...
We're getting ahead of ourselves.
Actually, I don't remember ever being introduced to Earl Rudder.
My older brother, so there's six years difference in our ages, and my older brother had been at Tarleton when Earl was.
And I sort of had my eye on him from looking at the angles.
It was strange.
In fact, I was no more than maybe 11 years old when I took note of him.
And he was a big football player, the captain and all that.
This little town, Minari.
And see, I lived 23 miles from there.
But they had a hotel that had the whole top floor was ballroom.
It had the best dances.
And that's where I first met her.
We started dancing together.
I was my brother's sister.
I knew who he was.
And right after college, you taught for one year?
I got the job.
He came down.
my senior year, earlier.
We'd been dating for a couple years already.
Only when he was, when I was home from school.
And so he came down and said I would apply in Brady.
All my friends went to Houston to preach, but I got the job in Brady.
And I taught one year, and that was depression.
And they had a rule that they wouldn't hire a married teacher.
Of course, I made the fantastic sum of $900 for the entire year.
$100 a month, and you taught nine months, and that's all you got paid.
And I was so young, and I guess full of pep, that I was sponsored for everything they had.
I was sponsored by the ball club, and I never...
I played a game.
That was before school, 7.30 in the morning.
And then I sponsored the cap squad after school.
And then I sponsored senior class.
So it was kind of a busy year.
And anyway,
We waited until I was re-elected for another year before letting the board know that we planned to get married.
And Earl told them that I would be glad to teach if they saw fit to change the rules.
But they didn't change it.
They just let me be the chief substitute.
And it wouldn't matter a whole lot because we were just there one more year.
And then he was made football coach.
See he was a football coach when I married him.
He was made football coach at Tarleton.
So that was 1938.
So we go to Tarleton and as I told him last fall when he was named Distinguished Alumnus up there, the first one they had named posthumously.

in my remarks i told him that he was doubly glad to get that job because in the first place he made 30 a month more than he'd made coaching in high school and the next reason was he could put me in back in school and have cook which he did did he really oh yeah of course he thought i was sorry strange because i had grown up on a ranch and did not have a milk with cow dress of chicken
But cooking, he just couldn't forgive that.
And I think the last straw was when he told me once that he thought because I'd grown up on the ranch that I surely know how to cook a pot of red beans.
So he told me that day, he said, I'm so hungry for a good pot of red beans.
And I thought, OK.
So I went to the grocery store and bought five pounds, came home, and put them all on the cook.
And they just had to do everything in my kitchen.
So with that, he decided he better let me have some fame in hometown.
So I guess it's helped a lot.
Where'd you get your training at?
That was at Tarleton's.
He was football coach there.
So he just put me in school.
And he was from Brady?
He was born in Brady?
No, he was born in Eden, which is...

very small it's a one traffic light crown to this day and that's where he was born there are two pictures in the high school in eden one is a general ira acre he was head of the uh all our air forces in european theater and in earl's picture so i guess they're still there i haven't been there in a long time but the last time i was there

anyone said that he helped pay his way to charlton by milking a cow he he paid his entire education except for five dollars his mother gave him seeing his dad really didn't want him to go to college because he said see earl had made his own money from the time he was seven years old and doing one thing another selling door-to-door very soon and then the time he was going
in high school, he was working in a drug store.
And his dad said, I think it'd be foolish for you to go to college because you're making more money now than I was when I married your mother.
But the coach, the football coach at Carlton had been through this a little time.
And his doctor had lunch at a little cafe there.
And he said to the owner, he said, do you have any good football players around here?
He said, well, we got one.
He said, it's rubber.
So he looked him up.
It didn't take him long to find him.
The town was so tiny.
And so I have this and a letter that this coach wrote to me three years after my husband's death.
But he told Earl, he said, if you'll come and play football, he said, we'll find a way for you to get through school.
Of course, they didn't make, they didn't give them anything, you know, for playing.
I said, well, they didn't have the free use of the uniform.
That was just about it.
He got a job waiting tables in the college dining room.
And he's still running kind of short of money.
And so he got a job at a drug store that was just across the campus.
So he was working those two jobs.
And at the end of his first year, he was elected captain for the following year.
And so the next fall, he started out with his two jobs.
He was still having just a rough time.
He just didn't think he could get by on what he was making.
So he went to see a coach one day right at lunchtime to tell him that he was going to have to go home, but he just couldn't make it.
Coach said, oh, Rudder said, just go on, and I'm getting ready to go to Lions Club, and you have to come back after lunch, and I'll talk to you.
So when he got to Lions Club, he told the membership, he said, look, we've got to figure out some way
to keep him in school.
He said, I'm about to lose my captain.
And so you just see what we can do to help him.
So they decided to buy a Jersey milk cow.
And they let him graze it around the football field and milk it and sell the milk to the dining hall.
And they still laugh up there and say that the first day he took his bucket to the dining hall to sell it, it wasn't quite full.
So they didn't pay him what he thought he was going to get.
So the next day when he dealt the cow, he was on the way to the dining hall with the milk.
Just happened to notice there was a water faucet.
He said from then on he always drived full bucket.
I guess that's true.
That's a good story.
Okay.
So you met General Rutter when he was a junior in college?
No, you were a junior in college and he was already a coach?
No, I was a freshman in college, and he was coaching today.
But his first year out of A&M, times were so tough then.
And he did all kinds of things to get through A&M.
See, he came down here for his last two years.
Graduated here in 1932.
But he couldn't get a job except for one with a highway department.
They were building a road between Eden and Menard.
And he was, his first year out of A&M with his degree, he took a job digging ditches for 25 cents an hour.
And then the next fall, he got the job coaching the baby.
When did we get married?
We got married in 1937, see?
I had finished Texas in 36, taught that one year in Brady.
And then we married in 1936.
And in 1941, he got off into the war, 1940?
Yeah.
We had our first child.
in Stephenville, in 40.
And when he was just about a year old, maybe a month or two after he was a year old, he was called into the service.
Because, see, he got his reserve permission when he graduated from A&M.
And he was first sent to Fort St. Houston.
And from there to infantry school in Fort Benning and then back to Fort St. Houston.
Then to the 83rd Division up in Camp Atterbury, Indiana.
By then we had a second child, that was 1942.
Were you following him along?
Oh yeah, until he went overseas.
So anyway, we lived in all kinds of places.
People would not believe, it would just sound like a crazy story if I mentioned how we had lived in some of those places.
But you did what you had to do.
And so he went overseas in November of 1943.
And so when he went overseas, I had to bring the two children and come back home.
And so we came back to stay in Brady because his brother and his
And back in 35, he was responsible for putting in a drugstore in Brady, which he and his brother all played together.
And then my parents would be just 36 miles from me.
They could be a lot of help and worry.
So we stayed there during the war.
And you had two children?
I had two children.
We were in two years apart.
Well, the first one was a son named James Earl Rudder, Jr., but they always called him Bud.
The next one was Anne, the daughter.
So during the war, you and the children went back home?
Stayed in David, uh-huh.
Until he came home?
Yeah.
What about his actions during the war?
Can you tell me about those?
Actually, when he was in the 83rd Division at Camp Atterbury in Indiana, the War Department decided that all divisions should put in some ranger training.
So they put him in charge of that.
And General Friedendahl went around the country looking at all the divisions
and inspecting a program for ranger training, and he decided that that was the best.
And so he named Earl to command the second ranger battalion, the first had been formed, commanded by General Darby.
And he did not come back from war.
He was killed late in the war.
And Earl commanded the second ranger battalion, Camp Forest, Tennessee, trained there, and then took them overseas.
And they trained in England, in Cornwall.
They had cliffs there.
When he found out what their mission was, it was really a tough one.
And so they trained in Cornwall, and they trained some on the Isle of Wight.
And their mission was to...
climb these 100-foot cliffs in Normandy, Pointe du Hoc, and knock out the six 155-millimeter guns that the Germans had placed there that could fire on Utah and Omaha beaches.
When the soldiers came across.
What?
When the soldiers came across the beaches.
Oh, yeah, when they landed.
They were to knock out these guns so the soldiers could land on those two beaches.
because his point jutted out right between the two beaches.
And everybody thought it was sort of a suicide mission, that there's no way to take a dip.
And General Bradley, in his book, A Soldier's Story, describes it as the most difficult assignment he ever gave a soldier in his entire career.
And so, for the D-Day mission,
Earl was given command of not only the 2nd, but the 5th battalion.
He could command both of them for the invasion.
And so there were only three companies out of the 2nd that went up the cliffs, D, E, and F. And the other companies, A and B, they landed on other parts of the invasion beaches.
And he handpicked 225 men for this mission.
And at the end of the first day, there were only 90 able to bear arms.
The way this mission was planned, timing was everything.
The battleship in the Channel, Battleship St.
Channels, were lobbing shells over onto the Pointe du Hte.
And at this point in time, they would stop shelling because at that time, the range was supposed to be at the foot of the cliff.
But as it happened, when they were loaded off the
ships that brought them across the channel into their small landing craft.
They were assigned a British guide boat.
And this British guide boat took them off course.
There was another point that looked very similar, but it was about four miles to the east, at least four miles, maybe further.
And so it didn't take long for my husband to realize that they were headed for the wrong point.
And he kept trying to tell this British guide boat that they were headed for the wrong point, but they ignored it.

And finally, he had just take command of his own little bunch of landing craft and turn them to the west toward the proper point, which meant, see, if they had gone in on time, the Germans would have been driven underground because they had a vast,
array of underground tunnels.
They couldn't stay up on the top with all the shelling.
So if they could have been there at the proper time, the Germans would have been totally surprised.
But at the time that they were supposed to be there, the shelling quit.
And yet they were far from being there, and the seas were very rough.
I think the waves were at least six feet high.
And so they had to come along parallel to the coastline.
And the Germans by then had had time, they were about 40 minutes late, had had time to come out of the underground
And so they were on top of the cliff waiting for them.
They were firing at them, and they were cutting the ropes that they were climbing up.
See, the way they would get up those cliffs, they had grappling hooks attached to ropes that they would fire by rocket off their little landing craft.
dig into the soil.
I'm not saying it's very good.
And then they'd find these ropes, and then they had some rope ladders that they had.
And they also had some, my husband had borrowed some ladders from the fire department in London, and they were in sections.
They put those together and put up on the face of the cliff.
But anyway, as I say, it was unfortunate that the
It couldn't have gone off on time, but it was not the fault of the rangers, it was the fault of the Buddhist guide boat.
But anyway, they were up there then, and it denied them their reinforcements that they were to have had.
If they didn't get the signal that they were up on the cliffs by a certain time, then the rest of the second and fifth battalions would land on Omaha Beach, which they did.
And then they'd have to fight over land to get to the ranges where it pointed to Hope.
So it was not until two and a half days later that the reinforcements got to them.
By then they had run out of ammunition, they'd run out of food, and they'd had several German counterattacks.
Of course they were
really outnumbered.
And the things looked pretty bleak there for a while.
Of course, on that day my husband was shot through the leg, but fortunately it didn't hit the bone.
And when he established his command post, he was inside of this open sort of a German bunker.

And there were two men, one on either side of him, and a shell came in from, I guess, one of the ships out in the channel, hit the side of this rock bunker, and it killed the men on either side of him, and he was...

left in the middle he got shrapnel in his arm and his leg and his hip actually that day so they considered he was wounded three times but he never left command of the of the rangers they had one doctor who actually in civilian life was a pediatrician but he kind of patched him up put bandage on and he kept going so anyway i think uh
that of all the challenges that he faced throughout his life, that was probably the worst.
And I think since he lived through that, I kind of think the challenges that came up later, he always could do because of having had that experience.
Do you think that the Lord changed him?
Oh, I do.
In fact, he said that war was such a terrible thing.
And that wasn't the end of it.
He was given command of the 109th Regiment in the 28th Division.
on the 8th of December, I believe it was, and on the 16th then, the Germans' last great offensive was out of the bush, and it hit right where his division was.
His regiment held the southern flank, and parts of the division were just absolutely all but wiped out.
So that was another tough experience for him.
So there's no doubt that the war changed him more than anything.
And so when he came home, he felt so thankful just to have survived it.
But he said, if you didn't want it to happen again, you better get to work on the home front.
And so he'd hardly bring it back.
He got home.
And he'd been gone two years.
And of course, I was so glad to get him home.
The War Department turned around and had him, put him in command of a Victor Loaning Train that had all sorts of war souvenirs.
And sent him all around the country selling war bonds.
So that kept him another, oh let's see, that was from September until two days before Christmas.
So he got home.
And then in April he was elected mayor.
We were in Brady.
And so he served as mayor for six years, three times.
And he was elected to the State Democratic Executive Committee.
And while on that, he got three plans for the governor.
He was Alan Shivers at the time.
And so in 1955,
The land commissioner had been, he was serving, I think he'd been elected to his ninth term.
He was head of the whole messianic organization in the state of Texas.
Most respected person.
But he saw an opportunity to make some money, but it was crooked.
He ended up in prison.
And he could tell what he was being caught up with.
And so he just said he, for personal reasons, he wasn't going to serve that term that he'd been elected to.
So that meant that the governor had to appoint somebody.
So the governor appointed Earl as land commissioner.
Mitch was the general land officer for this property.
That was a big job, and things were in such a glorious mess.
But he waded into that and straightened it out, ran for re-election, got re-elected.

And in the middle of his second term, the board of directors that was called in at A&M came and wanted him to come here as vice president, actually, but with the understanding that he was to run this campus.
And then the following year, he was made president of A&M.
Of course, many, many things happened to change the face of the university during his administration.
What were some of those things that changed Hayden?
Well, at the beginning of the spring semester of 1958, the spring he came here,
And I'd say he left in the middle of his term that he'd been elected to.
We worked very hard to get him re-elected at campaign headquarters in our home in Austin.
And, like I say, uh, but when the NM wanted to come here, that was it.
Uh, at the time we got here, there were less than 7,000 students.
I think there'd been a little more than 7,000 in the fall, the start of the fall semester.
But, of course, it dropped off a little bit at the start of the second semester.
And it was all male, all military.
The name was Agricultural Mechanical College.
And integration had not taken place.
So during his administration, girls were admitted.
That was 1963.
The name change took place the same year.
And they didn't want to give up the A&M part of the name.
See, so many land grant colleges over the nation, they took like LSU, Louisiana State.
It was a land grant college.
That was a trend.
But the former students didn't want that.
They wanted that A&M .
But it didn't stand for agricultural mechanical anymore.
So they just decided to call it Texas A&M University.
That was in 63.
Integration, I'm not sure what year that took place.
But it was done smooth itself.
No problem.
Of course, during the 60s,
There was a lot of student unrest at other schools, but not here, not at A&M.
That was one thing that, he had been a student, General Jim Hannigan, that he had gone to Washington and looked for somebody that was young enough and just retired from the Army.
And the Prima, too, I believe, pretty well kept things under control.
Although there was a group that came over here and tried to organize, but they had that cord so organized against it that they never got hold of it.
How did they maintain control?
Well, they just had that much discipline.
It was so much smaller then compared to now.

they came over here i guess in school where i went and tried to organize had their literature and all that but they didn't they didn't get the first place and they sent them in from oh i don't know exactly how far away but trying to organize things like that but they just let it be known they weren't going to stand for it the administration let it be known
In 1965, he was named head of the entire system.
So he was still president of A&M here, but head of the whole system.
And he just, he never stopped.
He just worked night and day.
And I say in 19, well, in fact, January of 1970, he got sick.
died in March, March 23rd, at the age of 59.
That's young.
Yeah, very young.
I don't know where we go from here.
So, you were older than he was?
He was six years older than I was.
Oh, I'm sorry.
I'm sorry.
I do know.
Okay, um...
Okay, I thought your...
But I never considered it.
I just, you see we had five children, and in all these things that he did, I know when, when the governor poached him about being mentioned at the general
I told him, I said, you do what you want to do because my work's cut out for me to produce the children.
And he had a kind of a system anyway.
He took care of his job and business.
I took care of the house and the children.
It worked out pretty well.
Was he really active with the children or things like that?
Well, he was all so busy with his job from the time they were seven.
Our youngest was only eight months old when he was made land commissioner.
So it pretty well fell my lot.
Of course, he did, you know, what he could.
Okay, you once said that Lyndon Johnson had offered positions to do no matter?
Yeah.
Can you tell me about that?
Well, it goes way back.
In 1948, when Lyndon Johnson ran for the Senate, he asked Earl, we were living in Brady, he asked Earl to be his campaign manager in the district, which had 16 or 18 counties, I've forgotten.
We lived close to where his opponent lived.
He said, now you can't carry this county because you're too close to where Colt Stevenson lived.
As it turned out, the county where we lived went for him by more votes than he won the statewide election by.
He only won the election by 87 votes statewide, which is unheard of.
That's why they call them landslide limits.
And so after that, anything that
Earl asked of him.
He always came through for him.
But when I'm looking at the picture of Lyndon Johnson over there, which reminds me of when we got it, they had asked us up to the White House in 66 to a dinner for Henry Cabot Lodge.
and, uh, flight experience for me earlier than the floor that I had.
And, uh, so the next morning after the... We stayed there in the White House up on the third floor, and the President's quarters were on the second floor.
And, uh, so we hadn't really had much of a chance to visit personally with him.
And the next morning, we were gonna leave fairly soon, and, uh, the President called and said to come down to the...
floor below, and I don't know if I should tell this or not, he was still in bed in his pajamas and his hair wasn't combed, he had newspapers scattered all around him, and had three TV screens going.
He was talking to Senator Snyder, and as we walked in, he said, you know, Senator, I can get nearly everybody to do what I ask them to do except Earl Rudder, and he won't do a blank thing.
Because he had offered, I can't tell you which things he had offered Earl.
Some in Washington and some were foreign opponents.
But Earl would always say, I'm sorry Mr. President, but I have brought too many good people to A&M to go off and leave.
Go off and leave.
So he wouldn't leave here.
And I guess it wasn't the easiest thing in the world to turn a president down, especially one like William Johnson.
Some of the things he brought at A&M, um, women were allowed in.
Yeah.
Coral was made optional.
Coral was made optional.
Uh-huh.

Well, uh, it boomed... more so after his death.
There's all these things that had been keeping it from going.
It was about 14,000-something at the time he died, which was double what it was when he came here.
But, uh...
It's like the lady said last night at this dinner for retiring professors.
Said he's the one that made the decision to let it go like that.
And of course, I think that's true.
What did he think about allowing women to go to A&M?
Well, he was for it, you see.
But the strange thing was, the student body, all male, was not.
They wanted it just like it was.
And especially these old eggs that were already out of A&M.
Some of them never did get over it.
They thought things had just gone to pop.
Because they wanted to be just like it was when they were students here.
But actually, the student body, when he got up before them and told them they were going to admit the girls, they booed him.
They also burned him in effigy out in front of the house.
Didn't they also burn the dog in effigy?
No.
They didn't burn the dog.
They just painted the dog.
They were always painting that funny bulldog that he named Ranger.
But when the matter of admitting the coeds came up,
This dog just waddled around all over campus.
Everybody that was in school knew and remembered him.
But they painted him with a sign that says, Maggie's Go Home.

And they booed them outside the house?
How long did they do that?

Who, Earl?
